      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process has been instrumental in expanding rights like reproductive freedom, LGBTQ+ rights, and workers' rights. For instance, it was used to strike down laws banning interracial marriage (Loving v. Virginia) and laws prohibiting gay couples from adopting children (Obergefell v. Hodges). Additionally, it's been used to limit corporate power, as seen in cases like Marbury v. Madison, which established judicial review, and more recently, in cases like Janus v. AFSCME, which protected public sector union rights. These examples demonstrate the significant impact of substantive due process on shaping modern liberty.",
      "source": "target",
